South Africa’s trade surplus eased to R4 billion ($283 million) in September from a revised R5.98 billion surplus in August as exports fell, data from the revenue agency showed on Tuesday. Exports dropped by 1.6% to R101.76 billion on a month-on-month basis in September, while imports inched up 0.4% to R97.76 billion, the South African Revenue Service said in a statement. On a cumulative basis the trade balance between January and September was at a R47.12 billion surplus compared to a R6.66 billion shortfall over the same period in 2016.   ($1 = R14.12)